    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/97aa8c37ffa60c4262955aefae56e605?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1443334,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1362755,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1362755/the8472",
                "reputation": 43508,
                "display_name": "the8472"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1479024540,
            "creation_date": 1479024540,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n<p>My application uses a big amount of memory; more than 100 Go.<\/p>\n<p>JMC tells me that they are SerialOld but I don't know what it exactly means<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n<p>If you are using the serial collector for a 100GB heap then long pauses are to be expected because the serial collector is single-threaded and one core can only only chomp through so much memory per unit of time.<\/p>\n<p>Simply choosing any one of the multi-threaded collectors should yield lower pause times.<\/p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>However, I don't know how to confrim (or not) this hypothesis; How to find which finalizer is time consuming.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n<p>Generally: Gather more data. For GC-related things you need to enabled GC logging, for time spent in java code (be it your application or 3rd party libraries) you need a profiler.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 40571810,
            "question_id": 40562665,
            "last_edit_date": 1592644375
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/147c5a9cc1feec049c50da791ac7d144?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 47283,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 139985,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/139985/stephen-c",
                "reputation": 723464,
                "display_name": "Stephen C",
                "accept_rate": 69
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1478953403,
            "creation_date": 1478953403,
            "body": "<p>Here is what I would do to investigate your finalizer theory.<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Start the JVM using your favorite Java profiler.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Leave it running for long enough to get a full heap.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Start the profiler.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Trigger garbage collection.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Stop profiler.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Now you can use the profiler information to figure out which (if any) <code>finalize<\/code> methods are using a large amount of time.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>However, I suspect that the real problem will be a memory leak, and that your JVM is getting to the point where the heap is filling up with unreclaimable objects.  That could explain the frequent \"SerialOld\" garbage collections.<\/p>\n\n<p>Alternatively, this could just be a big heap problem.  100Gb is ... big.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 40562793,
            "question_id": 40562665
        }
    ],
